VARICELLA, NEONATAL (5)
=======================
[1]
From: csanders <csanders@healthnet.zw>
Date: Thu, 11 Jan 96 14:24:10 +0200
According to "Dermatology and Venereology" (Braun-Falco ed.),
varicella infection in the first trimester of pregnancy may lead
to congenital abnormalities in about 1% of the cases. There appears
to be no such risk in the second and third trimester. If a maternal
varicella occurs at the end of pregnancy about 25% of
the neonates will develop clinical symptoms. The course the infection
takes is more severe in the infant, the closer the maternal infection
is to the delivery date. Pregnant women with a documented exposure and
without acquired immunity should receive VZIG [varicella-zoster immune
globulin], which is useless after the manifestations of varicella have
appeared. In the above case it was warranted to give the neonate
VZIG at birth which hopefully has modified the clinical symptoms.
--
